✅ What is a Webhook?
A Webhook is a way for an external service (like GitHub) to notify Jenkins when an event occurs (e.g., a push to a repository). Instead of Jenkins polling GitHub, GitHub sends an HTTP POST request to Jenkins with details about the event.

Why Use Webhooks?

Reduces unnecessary polling.
Immediate build trigger after code changes.
Efficient for CI/CD pipelines.

✅ Webhook Setup for GitHub → Jenkins
Go to GitHub Repository → Settings → Webhooks → Add Webhook

Payload URL Syntax:
http://<JENKINS_SERVER>:8080/github-webhook/

Example:
http://192.168.1.100:8080/github-webhook/

If Jenkins is behind a proxy or uses HTTPS:
https://yourdomain.com/github-webhook/

Content Type:
application/json

Events to Trigger:
Usually "Just the push event" or "Send me everything".

✅ Jenkins Configuration
Install GitHub Integration Plugin or GitHub Plugin.
In your Jenkins job:\
Check "GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling" under Build Triggers.

✅ Default Jenkins Workspace Path
When Jenkins builds a job, it creates a workspace directory:
/var/lib/jenkins/workspace/<JOB_NAME>/

Example:
/var/lib/jenkins/workspace/first/
Inside this folder:
Source code cloned from Git.
Build artifacts generated during the job.

✅ Pipeline Location
Jenkins pipelines are usually defined in:
Jenkinsfile (stored in your Git repo).
Or inside Jenkins job configuration (if using classic UI).

✅ Quick Summary

Webhook Payload URL:
http://<jenkins-server>:8080/github-webhook/
Default Jenkins Workspace Path:
/var/lib/jenkins/workspace/<job-name>/
